<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-596-040  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 596 040.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  June 21 1990 v16 n13 p21(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DBMS helps Canadian forecasters. (Canada's government weatherservice will run the Empress relational database managementsystem) (from Empress Software Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Frangini, Monica.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Canada's Atmospheric Environment Service will upgrade its weatherforecasting system.andP;  The computerized weather data analysissystem, which is now contained in a variety of systems runningabout 300 applications, will be streamlined.andP;  The replacementsystem will be based on computers from Hewlett-Packard runningEmpress relational data base management software from EmpressSoftware (Greenbelt, MD).andP;  The flexible new configuration willanalyze meteorological data in a systematic way, managing data andallowing the interaction of applications.andP;  Under the Empresssystem, the number of applications will be reduced to about 50.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (products)Empress Software Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Product:   Empress RDBMS (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     Canada. Atmospheric Environment ServiceMeteorologyGovernment AgencyData AnalysisRelational DBMS.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DBMS helps Canadian forecastersandM;Canada's government weather service has replaced its entire weatherforecasting system with one that will run a relational database managementsystem (RDBMS) from Greenbelt, Md.-based Empress Software Inc.andM;Originally put in place in the mid-'70s, Canada's computerized weather datasystem is used by regional meteorologists to develop forecasts for aviation,forestry and general public use.andM;Over its 18-year life, the system had grown into a &quot;hodge-podge&quot; of over 250applications &quot;shoehorned&quot; into outdated minis, with the majority ofapplications in place merely to manage data and permit different programs tointeract, said Empress president John Kornatowski, from the company'sresearch and development centre in Toronto.andM;&quot;On top of all the problems the AES (Atmospheric Environment Service) didn'thave an engine underneath that could manage their data in one unified andcoherent way, so they decided they would have to update,&quot; said Kornatowski.andM;Parameters were developed for a modern, flexible system that would not onlymeet current needs, but have reserve capacity for growth and advancedapplications.andP;  Bids for development hardware called for concurrentrecommendations for a RDBMS.andM;The winning proposal was from Hewlett-Packard, with Empress as its choice asRDBMS partner.andP;  &quot;We were looking for an open system architecture and that waswhat Empress was offering,&quot; said Don Dueck, project manager for the AES.andM;The AES ran a series of operational tests pitting Empress against anothermajor database.andP;  Empress was also chosen because its database kernel levelC-interface (MX and MR) routines offer direct access to database structure,said Kornatowski.andM;&quot;The AES will be able now to not only find out about trends for local areas,but also worldwide, on things such as temperature, air pressure and windspeed.andP;  They're looking at getting the information back on a real-timebasis.&quot;andM;Once completed, Canada's weather forecasting system will be running Empressat nine regional sites, plus a research and development, training andmaintenance operation.andP;  The system is also expected to be installed in fourmilitary locations.andP;  With Empress doing the bulk of the information handling,the system's current 250-300 applications will be reduced to about 50, saidKornatowski.andM;The system will also archive forecasts for use in aircraft accidentinvestigations.andO;</TEXT></DOC>